Secure containers leverage hardware virtualization to isolate container sandboxes, enabling dedicated guest kernels to mitigate shared kernel attacks prevalent in traditional systems. However, existing approaches struggle with a fundamental trade-off: VM-based solutions (e.g., Kata) prioritize performance but lack elasticity and on-demand usage for volatile and bursty workloads, while lightweight methods (e.g., gVisor) rely on the host kernel for dynamic resource management at the cost of significant performance degradation due to guest-host dependencies. We present SKernel, a production-proven secure container system that resolves this trade-off through a novel split-kernel architecture. Observing I/O stacks dominate performance for cloud-native apps, SKernel decouples the guest kernel into two components: SKernel-R (resource management via host collaboration) and SKernel-D (high-performance I/O operations without host involvement). Key innovations of SKernel include (1) a fast syscall forwarding approach that minimizes context switch overheads; (2) a device passthrough-based network stack that offers improved compatibility and resource flexibility, combined with an advanced thread model and I/O notification mechanism to handle volatile and bursty workloads; (3) a file descriptor-based container filesystem that enhances security, eliminates unnecessary indirection, and reduces costs. Macrobenchmarks evaluations show SKernel achieves 4.49× throughput gains over gVisor while matching its elasticity. SKernel reduces CPU usage compared to runc under production workloads, supporting over 2,000 long-running microservices applications across 40,000+ nodes (with 100,000+ secure containers) at Ant Group. SKernel represents a milestone as a production-ready secure container that delivers both efficiency and elasticity.